How to win an AI Hackathon, without using AI

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:32.000
How to win an AI Hackathon, without using AI

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:02.000
How to win an AI Hackathon, without using AI

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:32.000
How to win an AI Hackathon, without using AI

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:02.000
How to win an AI Hackathon, without using AI

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:32.000
How to win an AI Hackathon, without using AI

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:02.000
How to win an AI Hackathon, without using AI

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:32.000
How to win an AI Hackathon, without using AI

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
hackathons, without using AI

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:38.000
hacking.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:40.000
I will explain the basics of

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:42.000
data, spatial data.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:46.000
Northumbrian water has two

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:48.000
sites in the UK, one by the

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:50.000
border in Northumbria in

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:52.000
England and down in the south.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:54.000
We have spatial data on that.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:56.000
We had time series.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:58.000
We had data on 15-minute

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:00.000
intervals, we had data on

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:02.000
that.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:04.000
We had leakage estimates, so

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:06.000
how much water was actually

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:08.000
lost due to leakage.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:10.000
We had flow rates.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:12.000
So in the UK, you can imagine

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:14.000
how the water sort of

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:16.000
authority, the water companies

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:18.000
have evolved over the last few

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:20.000
decades.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:22.000
And we have something called a

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:24.000
DMA.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:26.000
It's a collection of zones of

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:28.000
postcodes, some are quite big,

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.000
some are quite small, and the

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:32.000
flow rate is just how much water

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:34.000
is passing through, how much

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:36.000
water is being used by people.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:38.000
We have the reported leaks,

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:40.000
it's basically an Excel spreadsheet

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:42.000
with some dates, times, postcodes

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:44.000
and sort of what the person said

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:46.000
over the phone.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:48.000
We have pipe size, so that was

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:50.000
measurements in metric, so

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:52.000
centimetres, millimetres.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:54.000
Imperial UK, Imperial US,

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:56.000
Imperial Roman, you name it, we

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:58.000
have pipe location.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:00.000
That was more

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:02.000
an indication rather than an exact

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:04.000
measurement. Again,

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.000
pipes have been laid over the UK for

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:08.000
decades, so

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:10.000
they knew there was a pipe on this road

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:12.000
somewhere on this road and

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:14.000
they just hoped for the best.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:16.000
We've got pipe type, so you've

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.000
got plastic, you've got metal.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:20.000
Turns out there's also asbestos,

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.000
which, to be honest, worried me

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.000
somewhat, but asbestos, we were told,

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:26.000
was fine as long as no one drills

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:28.000
into it, so we're all safe.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:30.000
We've got social data,

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:32.000
that's basically saying

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:34.000
who's living in the area,

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:36.000
is it students, is it families, is it business,

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:38.000
what sort of mixture. We've got weather,

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:40.000
rain, sun,

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:42.000
not so often,

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:44.000
but how much rain we've got,

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:46.000
how much business, what sort of

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.000
businesses are nearby, what their usage

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:50.000
and then we've got stuff.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:52.000
What I'm guessing is someone had

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.000
a week to put this data together.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
The first four days, they got all

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:58.000
the stuff on the right, and then

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:00.000
they spent the last day just putting in

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:02.000
other stuff, and I can't remember what the other stuff

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:04.000
was, but it's just general stuff, so

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:06.000
it might be interesting. So this is what we

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.000
had.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:10.000
And the problem set up that

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:12.000
we were given is

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:14.000
a very standard,

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:16.000
I would say, machine learning

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:18.000
framework. So we've

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:20.000
got all this data, all

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:22.000
the data that you would think would give

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:24.000
you an insight to leakage.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.000
And we've

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:28.000
got all the previous results, so we've got

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:30.000
leakage from the past of

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:32.000
two, three, five years.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:34.000
We've got

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:36.000
covariates or predictors that we

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:38.000
think would be useful, so

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:40.000
weather, businesses,

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:42.000
pipe type, pipe size.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:44.000
Intuitively, you'd think

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:46.000
if the pipe was older, then it might break.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:48.000
Intuitively, you'd think

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.000
if a pipe is made of lead,

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:52.000
then that's more likely to have a leak than a pipe

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:54.000
made of plastic.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:56.000
And so we're led up to

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:58.000
this very classic machine learning

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.000
problem of

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
lots of data, now put it into

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:04.000
your computer, turn the handle, and

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.000
try and predict what's going to happen.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:08.000
And in my head, I had this

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:10.000
amazing algorithm

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:12.000
that would tell someone

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:14.000
the precise coordinates of where the next leak

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:16.000
was going to happen, and engineers would

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:18.000
rush out and fix the leak before anything

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:20.000
would happen. That's why I thought it would happen.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.000
So this is me,

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:24.000
approximately like this, and

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:26.000
I worked hard all

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:28.000
day. So this was a Wednesday,

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:30.000
and I started coding

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.000
about quarter past nine on a Wednesday.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:34.000
So I just got the data, and I opened up

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.000
the folder, and I

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.000
looked at it, and I automatically went

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:40.000
to work. So I was a

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:42.000
dplyr machine. Hardly would have been proud

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.000
that this was

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:46.000
amazing. It

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:48.000
turns out that there's

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:50.000
multiple ways of spelling DMA.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.000
You'd think there's only one way of spelling DMA,

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:54.000
but they spell DMA multiple times,

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:56.000
so there's lots of left joins, right joins,

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:58.000
every join you can imagine.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:00.000
I even did some AI

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:02.000
or regression, as I

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:04.000
like to call it. So I did some regression,

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:06.000
I even did some

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:08.000
boosty, baggy tree things

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:10.000
to try and predict what was happening.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:12.000
I was working hard all day.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.000
I was doing what I was told.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:16.000
This is Seb,

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.000
an exact likeness,

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.000
and Seb had a different strategy. So we were on the same

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:22.000
team. So Seb is also in the booth

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:24.000
at Jumping Rivers at San Francisco,

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:26.000
so please go and embarrass him about this.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
So Seb spent all day drinking

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.000
coffee.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.000
And Seb ate Hobnobs as well.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:34.000
So if you don't know what a Hobnob is, it's a top

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:36.000
class biscuit made in the UK.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:40.000
And Seb asked questions.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:42.000
So in this room there were 10 teams,

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:44.000
and then there were a bunch of tables where people

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:46.000
from Northumbrian Water were there

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:48.000
ready to answer questions.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
And there were some people who were engineers,

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:52.000
there were some people who were sort of in charge

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:54.000
of the analytics, some people who were in charge of

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:56.000
customer service, just, you know,

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:58.000
people in tables who were waiting

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.000
for questions. So Seb would walk around

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:02.000
drinking his coffee, eating his Hobnobs

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.000
and having a nice jolly old time

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
while I was working hard.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.000
And I was

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.000
I have to be honest, okay?

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:12.000
So I was doing

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.000
all the work,

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:16.000
and I wanted to eat Hobnobs, and I wasn't

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:18.000
getting very many Hobnobs.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:20.000
I was drinking lots of coffee,

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:22.000
and if I'm being truthful,

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
I sort of started Jumping Rivers to avoid

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:26.000
doing work, you know, that's what all

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
founding a company is, it's about skiving from work.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.000
And, well, I seemed to

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
be doing lots of work, and Seb seemed to be wandering

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:34.000
around doing no work whatsoever.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.000
So,

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.000
do you remember back at the start,

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:40.000
the goal of the

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.000
hackathon was to reduce leaks by

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.000
20%.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.000
And that's sort of an obvious thing,

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:48.000
you know, who wouldn't want to reduce

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:50.000
leaks by 20%?

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.000
But a more obvious question,

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.000
or a less obvious question is, why,

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:56.000
you know, why 20%?

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:58.000
You know, why reduce leaks?

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:00.000
You know, is it a big problem?

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.000
And, after

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.000
chatting with a few people,

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:06.000
Seb found out, and essentially

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:08.000
they get charged a lot.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:10.000
Okay?

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.000
So, they're wanting to reduce leaks

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.000
because they're going to be charged an awful

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.000
lot of money. And

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:18.000
next year they're going to be charged even more

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:20.000
money, and the year after that they're going to be charged

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:22.000
even more money again.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.000
So each year they're going to get charged more and more money

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:26.000
for having leakage.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:28.000
So, the goal

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
wasn't to reduce leaks by 20%,

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.000
the goal

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:34.000
was really to reduce the amount lost due

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:36.000
to leakage. And

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:38.000
they're both similar ideas,

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:40.000
but if at the end

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:42.000
of the year you had 10,000 leaks

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:44.000
but lost very little water,

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:46.000
then that solves the second one

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
but not the first one. And that's

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.000
what they're wanting, they're wanting to reduce the amount

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.000
lost due to leakage. They didn't really care

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
about leaks, it was just the overall amount.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
So that's the first

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:58.000
thing.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:00.000
Second one is, how do you

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.000
estimate leakage?

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:04.000
Now, in the UK, you pick up a newspaper

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:06.000
and you read something

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:08.000
like the amount lost due to leakage

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:10.000
was 5,323 litres

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:12.000
and 3 teaspoons.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.000
And you think,

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.000
Dave got that measured, that's accurate.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:18.000
Lots of decimal places,

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:20.000
you know exactly what's going on.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:22.000
This isn't made up.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:24.000
Well, what happens

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:26.000
in practice is you have a DMA,

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.000
so a DMA is just a collection of zones,

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:30.000
so postcodes. Again, some are quite

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.000
big. And the

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.000
thought process goes, well,

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:36.000
we know how much water is going

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.000
into the DMA, we know how much water is going

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.000
out, that's how much water is being used.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:42.000
And, well, no one would use

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.000
water at 3 o'clock in the morning.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:46.000
So any water being used

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:48.000
at 3 o'clock in the morning must be a leak.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.000
Which

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.000
isn't the most precise

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.000
of measurements when you think about it

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:56.000
over the course of two seconds.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.000
And Northumbrian Water know this.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:00.000
They know this.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:02.000
It's not a surprise, they know this measurement is

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:04.000
shall we say noisy

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:06.000
or imprecise.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:08.000
There's nothing they can do about it.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.000
And we're currently working with another company

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:12.000
to actually measure soil temperature

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:14.000
and do a bit of prediction.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:16.000
But what we have on that day is

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.000
that's the column

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.000
that says leakage.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:22.000
It's the minimum flow rate at 3 o'clock in the morning.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:24.000
Would you believe that on New Year's Day

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:26.000
the leakage goes

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.000
through the roof and turns people up at 3 o'clock

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:30.000
in the morning? So that's what they have.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:32.000
What do you

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.000
need to fix leaks?

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:36.000
Well, you need an engineer

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
and you need data.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.000
So the engineer is obvious.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:42.000
You need someone to go out there,

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:44.000
probably in a van, with some tools to fix

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:46.000
a leak.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:48.000
What data do we need?

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.000
Well,

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.000
when an engineer goes out,

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:54.000
there's a leak at this region.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:56.000
Well, they want to know

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.000
what's the flow rate, how much water is being

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
used? What's the pipe type?

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:02.000
Is it steel? Is it plastic?

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:04.000
Is it asbestos?

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:06.000
What's the historical

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.000
leakage? Was there someone in the team

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:10.000
that went there last week and perhaps

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:12.000
it's the same thing again?

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:14.000
What's the weather?

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:16.000
Is it sunny? Is it raining?

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:18.000
They need to be able to predict this

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
and it could cause problems. Traffic?

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
Allegedly, they're not allowed to just

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
dig up roads when they feel like it.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
So if it's a main road,

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
they have to schedule that

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.000
at night time. Crime?

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:32.000
Do they need to bring a friend

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:34.000
to watch the van when they're going looking for leaks?

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.000
And this takes them two hours per

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:40.000
day to get this information.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.000
So every single day, an engineer walks in

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:44.000
and they say there's a leak

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:46.000
at this area and they spend two hours

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
getting all this information.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
All this information that we've just

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.000
been given for the hack.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:54.000
There's 35 engineers.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:56.000
Engineers aren't

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:58.000
cheap and

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:00.000
currently have, every morning,

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
two hours that five engineers spend

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
trying to get all this data together.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.000
So our solution

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.000
is not to try and predict leaks.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.000
When I say our, this was Seb's solution to be perfectly honest

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.000
but I'll go for our now.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
Our solution is not to try and predict

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:16.000
where leaks are going to happen, but to reduce

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:18.000
engineering time.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:20.000
We can get that two hours down

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:22.000
to about 10 or 15 minutes.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:24.000
It's just giving them

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:26.000
the data that they need.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
And this is relatively easy

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.000
and it's definitely doable.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:32.000
There's not a sort of R squared

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.000
or predictive value or anything like that.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
It's just about, they have data

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.000
in one place, we're wanting to make it

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.000
accessible in another. So this we can

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:42.000
definitely do.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.000
Now, we're now in day two

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.000
of the hack.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:48.000
And on the second half of the day

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.000
we have to do a presentation of what we've built.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
So we've got half a day

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:54.000
to do an app, and there's myself and Seb.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:56.000
So what we need to do is we need to

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:58.000
decide what we're going to make

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.000
and decide what to

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:02.000
bluff, or lie,

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.000
or pretend, or whatever you want to call it.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.000
So for example,

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:08.000
if we can demo a single DMA,

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:10.000
we don't

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.000
need to show two, three, four, five.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:14.000
We can do one, we don't need to do more.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.000
If we can display pipe location,

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:18.000
we don't need to

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.000
tell them about pipe type, that's obvious.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
We must be able to do it.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.000
So we've decided what to make and what to bluff.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.000
So this is a screenshot

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.000
of the winning app.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.000
This first screenshot contains lots of bluffing.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.000
So for example, in the top left-hand

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:34.000
corner, there's a little person that

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:36.000
indicates we've got authentication.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:38.000
We can do authentication, we do authentication

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:40.000
for our customers. We did not do authentication

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:42.000
on that half a day.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:44.000
We've got some high-priority DMAs

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:46.000
all bluffed.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
We can do that. We didn't need to do that in a day.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.000
Here

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:52.000
we've got a screenshot of

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:54.000
what an engineer could possibly see.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:56.000
So this was a long

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:58.000
column of different graphs

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.000
and different data. The first couple

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
of graphs were nice and busy and interactive.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.000
The last

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.000
few graphs were a bit more static in nature.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:08.000
And if you look at that little

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.000
blue slider,

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.000
when that was clicked on,

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.000
the graph was going grey, and that

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
was indicating that it wasn't going to be part

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:18.000
of an overall report the engineer

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:20.000
would take with them.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:22.000
Also an idea about taking a picture

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.000
and then being able to upload it onto the app.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:26.000
Again, we didn't

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:28.000
do this. It was just an indication.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:30.000
And this was all done using

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:32.000
lots of dplyr, ggplot,

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:34.000
Shiny app,

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:36.000
and all done in half a day.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.000
So the app

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:40.000
has now been used in production. I'm the

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.000
second person on the right, the tall

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.000
baldy chap. And I would love

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:46.000
to show you screenshots, but

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:48.000
because it's got national

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.000
infrastructure data, it's got

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:52.000
locations of pipes, we can't just

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
show screenshots easily.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:56.000
So that was when we won it two years ago.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.000
We also won it this year as well.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:00.000
So sorry for bragging,

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:02.000
but we won this year's hackathon as well.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:04.000
And we also won that one as well.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:06.000
So I'm not really sorry at all about bragging.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:08.000
I'm now just bragging completely.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:10.000
So,

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:12.000
summary.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:14.000
It's obvious, but think

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.000
about your problem. And if someone

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.000
told me before the hack, I would say, of course

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.000
you'll think about your problem.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.000
But I really didn't. I jumped in with both feet.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:24.000
I'm good at dplyr,

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:26.000
I'm good at R, I'm good at

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:28.000
building models, and I went straight

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:30.000
for that.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:32.000
And that's not the best way.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:34.000
Talk to people, ask them

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:36.000
what the problem really is.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:38.000
Also, don't send me to

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:40.000
a hackathon without others. So the one

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.000
hackathon that we've lost is the only one

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:44.000
that I've been to by myself.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.000
So that's somewhat embarrassing.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.000
So I'm now in this strange situation

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:50.000
where if the team go on a hack, I'm not sure

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:52.000
if I want them to win or lose, because, yeah.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.000
Anyway,

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.000
so thank you very much for listening.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.000
Sorry I couldn't join you

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:00.000
in San Francisco.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:02.000
It's really painful watching Twitter

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:04.000
and just seeing all this. Isn't our

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:06.000
conference absolutely wonderful?

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:08.000
So it's painful over in Newcastle.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.000
And by all means, please

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.000
come over and say hi, not to me,

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:14.000
but to Seb and the others

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:16.000
at the stall, and thank you very much

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:18.000
for listening. Thanks.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:20.000
Thank you.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:28.000
Thank you so much, Colin. That was great.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:30.000
Do you have any advice on where to find some

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:32.000
hackathons in North America?

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:36.000
Not so many.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
Not so much.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.000
Typically,

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:42.000
one should know

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:44.000
would be my answer. I think

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:46.000
you've caught me with that question.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:48.000
I suspect user groups

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:50.000
